Data-based Statistical Decision Model

Lecture 7 - Model evaluation and variable selection

Sungkyu Jung

Choosing models in Multivariate linear regression

In the multiple linear regression model, we assume that the response Y is a linear function of predictors, plus a constant, plus noise: \[ Y = \beta_0 +β_1X_1 +β_2X_2 +\cdots + β_pX_p + ε.\]

Sometimes we need to choose from two or more possible models. For example,

\[ Y = \beta_0 +β_1X_1 +β_2X_2 + ε,\] \[ Y = \beta_0 +β_1X_1 +β_2X_2 + \beta_3X_1X_2 + \beta_4 X_1^2 + \beta_5 X_2^2 + ε.\]

How do we decide which model to choose?

Recall:

  • We are comparing two linear models.

  • Both models are fitted by minimizing the in-sample MSE.

  • The bigger model is guaranteed to have a smaller MSE.

Training Error vs. Generalization Error

Recall: For a model \(Y = m({\mathbf x}) + \epsilon\), let \(\hat{m}({\mathbf x})\) be the fitted model on our data.

The in-sample MSE, or training MSE, is \[T = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2.\]

How well will \(m\)􏰉 predict in the future? Imagine a new data point \((X, Y )\) where \(X = (X_1, \ldots , X_p)\). Our prediction of Y using our model is \(m(X)\).

The generalization MSE, or Prediction MSE, is \[G = E \left( (Y - \hat{m}(X))^2 \right)\]

  • \(G\) is usually larger than \(T\).
  • Since we really want to use the model that will predict future observations well, we want the model with the smallest generalization MSE.

Comparison between Training and Generalization MSEs

To be concrete, imagine we observe new data at the same \(X\), i.e.

  • Training Data: \(Y_i = {\mathbf x}_i\beta + \epsilon_i\), \(i =1 ,\ldots, n\).

  • (Imaginary) New Data: \(Y_i' = {\mathbf x}_i\beta + \epsilon_i'\), \(i =1 ,\ldots, n\).

(See that we have the same \({\mathbf X}\) but different noise \(\epsilon_i'\).)

Then by computing \(\hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i) = \hat{Y}_i = ({\mathbf H}{\mathbf Y})_{i}\), compare

  1. In-Sample MSE : \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2\),

  2. Out-of-Sample MSE: \(\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y'_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2\).

It can be shown that on average

  1. In-Sample MSE is smaller than Out-of-Sample MSE;

\[E\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2 \right] < E\left[\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y'_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2 \right].\]

  1. The difference is exactly \(2\sigma^2(p+1)/n\);

\[E\left[ \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2 \right] = E\left[\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n(Y_i - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i))^2 \right] - \frac{2}{n}\sigma^2(p+1).\]

Optimism

  • Re-writing the above, \[E\left[ \mbox{In-Sample MSE} \right] = \mbox{"True MSE"} - \frac{2}{n}\sigma^2(p+1).\]

  • The term \[\frac{2}{n}\sigma^2(p+1)\] is optimism, the amount of bias, by which its in-sample MSE systematically under-estimates its true MSE.

  • Large optimism gives the model more opportunities to seem to fit well.

Strategies on data-based model selection

  1. Always compare Generalization MSE (or True MSE if possible)

  2. Option 1: Directly approximate “True MSE” by either data-splitting or Cross-Validation.

  3. Option 2: Approximate “True MSE” by In-Sample MSE + (approximated) optimism (Mallow’s \(C_p\) and information criteria).

Cross-Validation

  • The best way to estimate generaliation error is cross-validation.

  • Recall that we can divide the data into two parts: Training (\(Y_i, {\mathbf x}_i\)) and Testing Data (\(Y_i^*, {\mathbf x}_i^*\))

  • We estimate True MSE \(E(Y - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}))^2\) by
    1. calculating \(\hat{m}\) from the Training data,
    2. estimating \(E(Y - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}))^2\) by the out-of-sample MSE: \[\hat{E}(Y - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}))^2 = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (Y_i^* - \hat{m}({\mathbf x}_i^*))^2.\]

  • Cross-Validation refers to repeating the splitting, and using the average of our-of-sample MSEs as the approximation of Generalization MSE.

  • [Historical note] Cross-validation goes back in statistics into the 1950s, if not earlier, but did not become formalized as a tool until the 1970s, with the work of Stone (1974). It was adopted, along with many other statistical ideas, by computer scientists during the period in the late 1980s–early 1990s when the modern area of “machine learning” emerged from (parts of) earlier areas called “artificial intelligence”, “pattern recognition”, “data mining”, “neural networks”, or indeed “machine learning”.

K-fold cross-validation

  • Randomly divide the data into K equally-sized parts, or “folds”. A common choice is \(K = 5\) or \(K = 10\).
  • For each fold
    • Temporarily hold out that fold, calling it the “testing set”.
    • Call the other \(K − 1\) folds, taken together, the “training set”.

– Estimate each model on the training set, and calculate the MSE of each model on the testing set. - Average MSEs over folds.

We then pick the model with the lowest MSE, averaged across testing sets.

Leave-one-out cross-validation

  • Leave-one-out cross-validation is just the \(n\)-fold cross validation.

Leave-one-out cross-validation: definition

  • Recall the steps towards the definition of cross-validated residual (in previous lecture).
    • Fit a linear regression line with all observation except \((y_i, {\mathbf x}_i)\), then predict the conditional mean of \(y_i\) at \({\mathbf X}= {\mathbf x}_i\);
    • Call the predicted value \[\hat{Y}_{i(−i)},\]
    • The intermediate value \[Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i(−i)}\]
  • The leave-one-out cross-validation score (LOOCV) is \[ \mbox{LOOCV} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i(−i)})^2.\]

Leave-one-out cross-validation: computation

  • In evaluating linear models, leave-one-out cross-validation is indeed faster than $K-folds.

  • It only requires to fit the model once (neither \(K\) times nor \(n\) times) \[ \mbox{LOOCV} = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \left(\frac{Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i}}{1- h_{ii}}\right)^2.\]

Leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV): approximation

By approximating \(h_{ii}\) by its average \(\bar{h} = \sum_{i=1}^n h_{ii} = (p+1)/n\) (and more), we get \[\begin{align} \mbox{LOOCV} &\approx \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n ({Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i}})^2 + 2\bar{h}\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n ({Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i}})^2 \\ &= \mbox{In-Sample MSE} + \frac{2\hat{\sigma}^2 (p+1)}{n} \end{align}\]

Mallows’ \(C_p\)

  • Recall \[\mbox{"True MSE"} = E\left[ \mbox{In-Sample MSE} \right] + \frac{2}{n}\sigma^2(p+1).\]

  • The Mallows \(C_p\) statistic just substitutes in a feasible estimator of \(σ^2\) into the optimism:

\[C_p = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n (Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i})^2 + \frac{2\hat{\sigma}^2 (p+1)}{n}.\]

  • Typically, \(C_p\) is computed for each model we consider, and \(\hat\sigma^2\) is estimated only once, with the largest model (to ensure unbiased estimation).

  • Note that \(C_p\) is just an approximation of LOOCV score, thus is an approximation of Generalization MSE.

Alternative form of \(C_p\).

  • We can think of \(C_p\) as follows:

\[ C_p = \mbox{In-Sample MSE}+ \mbox{(penalty)}.\]

From one point of view, the penalty is just an estimate of the bias. From another point of view, it’s a cost we’re imposing on models for having extra parameters.

  • Oftentimes, Mallows \(C_p\) is altenatively defined as

\[C_p' = \frac{n}{\hat\sigma^2}C_p = n\frac{\mbox{In-Sample MSE}}{\hat\sigma^2} - n + 2p.\]

  • These are equivalent, and we seek a model with smaller \(C_p\).

Information criteria

An information criterion is defined for each model, say \(S\), and has the form:

\[\mbox{Information} = \mbox{In-Sample Performance} + \mbox{(Penalty)}.\]

  • Two famous criateria:
    • Akaike information criterion (AIC)
    • Schwarz’s Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)
  • Both can be used for any model (not only linear models!)

AIC

  • Akaike information criterion (AIC) is

\[\mbox{AIC}(S) = -2 L_S + 2 dim(S).\]

  • \(L_S\) is the log-likelihood of the model \(S\), evaluated at the maximum likelihood estimate.

  • \(dim(S)\) is the “dimension” of the model \(S\), i.e. the number of free parameters in \(S\).

  • Larger model (model with many predictors): \(-2L_S\) is smaller, but \(dim(S)\) is larger.

  • More parsimonious model (model with few predictors): \(-2L_S\) is larger, but \(dim(S)\) is smaller.

A toy data example

  • Let’s take the famous Boston data (with \(13\) predictors), and add 20 fake predictors.

  • We will compare models \(S_6\) through \(S_{33}\), where the model \(S_q\) means that we are including the first \(q\) variables.

  • In-Sample MSE should be smaller for larger \(q\).

  • Smallest LOOCV score or AIC should be from the model without the fake predictors.

library(MASS)
library(tidyverse)
Bos_fake <- cbind(Boston[,c(14,1:13)], matrix(rnorm(nrow(Boston)*20),ncol = 20)  )
pmax <- ncol(Bos_fake) - 1

Infosave <- list()
for(p in 6:pmax){
  out <- lm(medv ~ . , data = Bos_fake[,c(1, 2:(p+1))])
  LOOCV <- mean(((Bos_fake$medv - fitted(out))/(1-hatvalues(out)))^2)
  Infosave[[p]] <- tibble(q = p, 
                          AIC = AIC(out), BIC = BIC(out),
                          MSE = mean(out$residuals^2), 
                          LOOCV = LOOCV)
}
Infosave <- bind_rows(Infosave) 
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,LOOCV)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,AIC)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,MSE)) + geom_line()

  • For the Gaussian linear model (i.e. we know the likelihood, and the LS estimate is the MLE) \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 +\cdots + \beta_p X_p + \epsilon\), \(\epsilon \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\),

\[L_S = −n(1 + \log 2\pi) − n \log MSE,\] and \(dim(S) = p+2\).

What AIC does

  • \(AIC(S)/n\) is an unbiased estimate of the expected log-probability the estimated parameters for the model \(S\) will give to a new data point which it hasn’t seen before, if the model is right.

  • This is the natural counterpart of expected squared error for more general distributions than the Gaussian.

  • Minimizing AIC \(\approx\) Minimizing Generalization Error rate

  • The model chosen by AIC may be a larger model than truth, as long as the chosen model predicts better than the truth (given data).

BIC

  • Schwarz’s Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) is

\[\mbox{BIC}(S) = -2 L_S + \log(n) dim(S),\] where \(n\) is the sample size.

  • Compare BIC with AIC; the penalty in BIC \(\log(n)dim(S)\) is stronger than \(2dim(S)\) of AIC, thus BIC tends to choose smaller models.

  • In fact, As \(n \to \infty\), if the true model is among those BIC can select among, BIC will tend to pick the true model.

Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,BIC)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,AIC)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,MSE)) + geom_line()

Comparison with K-fold CV

We should compare the LOOCV \(\approx C_p \approx AIC \approx BIC\) with a K-fold cross-validation score. A K-fold CV can be manually implemented, but there are many options in R. Two popular options:

  • cv.glm() in boot package

  • cv.glmnet() in glmnet package; will revisit this later.

Let’s forget about “g” in glm for now. It means “generalized”, and a special case is simply lm.

Cross-validation using cv.glm()

  • Fit a linear model using glm()
out <- glm(medv ~ crim + zn , data = Boston) # this just fits a linear model 
out$coefficients
## (Intercept)        crim          zn 
##  22.4856281  -0.3520783   0.1161091
  • Compare the coefficient estimates from those of lm()
lm(medv ~ crim + zn , data = Boston)$coefficients
## (Intercept)        crim          zn 
##  22.4856281  -0.3520783   0.1161091

To compute the \(K\)-fold CV score, use cv.glm() in boot package.

library(boot)
cv.glm(Boston, out, K = 5)$delta[1]
## [1] 65.35782
  • In fact, we can compute LOOCV score as well.
out <- glm(medv ~ crim + zn , data = Boston)
cv.glm(Boston, out)$delta[1] # By not specifying K, we set K = n (i.e. Leave-one-out)
## [1] 65.84389
mean(((Boston$medv - fitted(out))/(1-hatvalues(out)))^2)
## [1] 65.84389
  • Using cv.glm() in computation for LOOCV score is not advisable. Why?

Let’s compare 5-fold CV scores with LOOCV scores

Infosave <- list()
for(p in 6:pmax){
  out <- glm(medv ~ . , data = Bos_fake[,c(1, 2:(p+1))])
  LOOCV <- mean(((Bos_fake$medv - fitted(out))/(1-hatvalues(out)))^2)
  KCV <- cv.glm(Bos_fake, out, K = 5)$delta[2]
  Infosave[[p]] <- tibble(q = p, 
                          KCV = KCV, 
                          LOOCV = LOOCV)
}
Infosave <- bind_rows(Infosave) 
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,LOOCV)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,KCV)) + geom_line()

What has gone wrong?

  1. Why is it flutuating?
    • Randomness in folding

  2. Remedies?

  3. Why use 5-fold over LOOCV?

One remedy: manual folding for all model evaluation

  • Folds before repetition!

  • We could use a combination of tidyverse-compatible packages to do this: modelr, purrr and broom (We will see these in labs)

  • The package caret has another powerful function createFolds() for creating random folds

library(caret)
Fold_index <- createFolds(1:nrow(Bos_fake), k = 5)

  • Then manually evaluate K-fold CV scores

  • See an example with a full model:

Out_of_Sample_MSE <- c()
for(k in 1:5){
  Train <- Bos_fake[-Fold_index[[k]],]
  Test <- Bos_fake[Fold_index[[k]],]

  out <- lm(medv ~ ., data = Train)
  test_pred <- predict(out, Test)
  Out_of_Sample_MSE[k] <- mean( (Test$medv - test_pred)^2 )
}
Out_of_Sample_MSE
## [1] 17.36201 21.45558 20.36229 27.37825 36.57446
( KCV <- mean(Out_of_Sample_MSE) )
## [1] 24.62652
  • Putting things altogether
Infosave <- list()
Fold_index <- createFolds(1:nrow(Bos_fake), k = 5) # Folds before evaluation
for(p in 6:pmax){
  # First compute KCV 
  Out_of_Sample_MSE <- c()
  for(k in 1:5){
    Train <- Bos_fake[-Fold_index[[k]],c(1, 2:(p+1))]
    Test <- Bos_fake[Fold_index[[k]],c(1, 2:(p+1))]
    out <- lm(medv ~ ., data = Train)
    test_pred <- predict(out, Test)
    Out_of_Sample_MSE[k] <- mean( (Test$medv - test_pred)^2 )
  }
  KCV <- mean(Out_of_Sample_MSE)
  
  # Then compute LOOCV 
  out <- lm(medv ~ . , data = Bos_fake[,c(1, 2:(p+1))])
  LOOCV <- mean(((Bos_fake$medv - fitted(out))/(1-hatvalues(out)))^2)
  
  Infosave[[p]] <- tibble(q = p, 
                          KCV = KCV, 
                          LOOCV = LOOCV)
}
Infosave <- bind_rows(Infosave) 
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,LOOCV)) + geom_line()
Infosave %>% ggplot(aes(q,KCV)) + geom_line()

  • Graphics look nice and good, but what are we forgetting?
    • K-fold CV scores are just estimates of true Generalization error
    • They do come with uncertainty
    • What’s the standard error of K-fold CV?
  • We will see a better handling at this, in variable selection.

Variable selection

  • When we compare models, ranging from the null model to the full linear model, a model corresponds to a subset of variables.

  • How Do We Fit All the Models?

  • Suppose there are p covariates. For each variable, we can decide to keep it in the model or throw it away. This means that there are \(2^p\) possible models.

  • If \(p = 100\) then \(2^p\) is equal to \(1,267,650,600,228,229,401,496,703,205,376\).

  • If possible, fitting all models is ideal.

  • Instead of fitting and comparing all models, we can use forward (or backward) stepwise regression, or lasso.

Forward Stepwise Regression

Forward stepwise regression works like this:

  1. Start by fitting the simplest model \(Y =β_0+ε\). Let \(S=\emptyset\).

  2. Next we consider all single variable models:

\[Y =β_0+β_1X_1+ε,\quad Y =β_0+β_2X_2+\epsilon, \ldots, .\]

We fit each of these and then choose the best one. “Best” means, lowest Cross-validation error, or lowest AIC etc. Add the best variable to \(S\). For example, suppose adding \(X_{7}\) was the best. Then \(S = \{7\}\) and our current estimated model is \(m(x) = \beta_0 + \beta_7 X_{7}\).

  1. Now consider adding another variable. So in this case we consider

\[Y =β_0+β_1X_1+\beta_7 X_7+ ε,\quad Y =β_0+β_2X_2+\beta_7 X_7 +\epsilon, \ldots, .\] Choose the best one and add it to \(S\). For example, if \(X_5\) was the best then \(S = \{5, 7\}\) and our current model estimate is \(m(x) = \beta_0 + \beta_5 X_5+\beta_7 X_{7}\). 􏰉􏰉􏰉 Note the the coefficients have changes. The estimate \(\hat{β}_7\) you get here will be differenr than the estimate in the previous step, because we are now fitting a two-variable model.

  1. Continue adding one variable at a time this way until you cannot add any more variables. Each step of the process gives us a new model. We have a set of models \(M_1, M_2, \ldots\).

  2. Now we estimate the prediction error of each model and choose the best one.

R practicalities: Forward variable selection

We can manually implement above procedure using add1() function.

null.model <- lm(medv ~ 1, data = Boston)
small.model <- lm(medv ~ lstat + rm + nox, data = Boston)
add1(null.model, scope = small.model , data = Boston)
## Single term additions
## 
## Model:
## medv ~ 1
##        Df Sum of Sq   RSS    AIC
## <none>              42716 2246.5
## lstat   1   23243.9 19472 1851.0
## rm      1   20654.4 22062 1914.2
## nox     1    7800.1 34916 2146.5

Variable lstat provides the smallest AIC, thus is added to the model. Next, we repeat the procedure:

model.1 <- lm(medv ~ lstat, data = Boston)
add1(model.1, scope = small.model , data = Boston)
## Single term additions
## 
## Model:
## medv ~ lstat
##        Df Sum of Sq   RSS    AIC
## <none>              19472 1851.0
## rm      1    4033.1 15439 1735.6
## nox     1       4.8 19468 1852.9

Next model is then medv ~ lstat + rm, since adding rm provides the smallest AIC.

model.2 <- lm(medv ~ lstat + rm, data = Boston)
add1(model.2, scope = small.model , data = Boston)
## Single term additions
## 
## Model:
## medv ~ lstat + rm
##        Df Sum of Sq   RSS    AIC
## <none>              15439 1735.6
## nox     1    14.898 15424 1737.1

Finally, we decide not to add nox in the model, as the AIC for the previous model is smaller.

Automated forward stepwise regression

Forward stepwise regression can be automated, using step() function

null.model <- lm(medv ~ 1, data = Boston)
full.model <- lm(medv ~ ., data = Boston)
step(null.model, scope = list(lower = null.model, upper = full.model), direction = "forward")
Automated Backward elimination

We can also begin with the full model, then remove variables one by one.

null.model <- lm(medv ~ 1, data = Boston)
full.model <- lm(medv ~ ., data = Boston)
step(full.model, scope = list(lower = null.model, upper = full.model), direction = "backward")

Best subset selection

  • When the number of predictors is not too large, we may want to fit all potential models.

  • This can automatically done using regsubsets() function in leaps package.

library(leaps)

Below, we are examining all \(2^p = 2^{13} = 8192\) models, and for each number of variables, keep only the model with “best” performance, in terms of the lowest AIC.
